A stream never ends, so how do you ever compute an average, or a count, or a sum? You can't wait for all the data, because the data never stops coming. The answer is windowing. You slice the endless stream into finite buckets of time, and you aggregate inside each bucket. And the key idea, the one that trips people up, is that the bucket is decided by event time, the moment something actually happened, not the moment Spark happened to see it. Pin one timeline in your head, twelve o'clock to twelve twenty-five, and watch three different ways to cut it.

The first and simplest is the tumbling window. Fixed size, back to back, no gaps and no overlap. Here every window is five minutes. Twelve hundred to twelve oh five is the first bucket, twelve oh five to twelve ten is the next, and so on down the line. Each window picks up exactly where the last one ended, like tiles laid edge to edge. The defining property is this, every event belongs to exactly one window. An event at twelve oh seven is in the second bucket, full stop. You write this as window of timestamp, comma, five minutes. Reach for tumbling whenever you want clean, non-overlapping reporting periods, hits per five minutes, revenue per hour, that kind of thing.

Now the sliding window. Same fixed size, but it advances by a smaller step, so the windows overlap. Here each window is ten minutes wide, but a new one starts every five minutes. So the first window covers twelve hundred to twelve ten, the next covers twelve oh five to twelve fifteen, the next twelve ten to twelve twenty, each one shifted over by the slide. Look at where they stack, they cover the same stretches of time more than once. And that changes everything about which window an event lands in. An event at twelve oh seven is now inside two windows at once, the first one and the second one. You write this as window of timestamp, comma, ten minutes, comma, five minutes, the second duration is the slide. Use sliding windows for smooth rolling metrics, a moving average, a trailing one-hour count updated every few minutes, anywhere a jumping tumbling window would feel too jerky.

The third one is different in kind, the session window. There's no fixed size at all. The window is defined by activity, and it closes only after a gap of silence. Set the gap to five minutes. The window opens when the first event arrives, and it keeps stretching as long as new events keep landing within five minutes of the last one. Watch the timeline. Events come in at twelve oh four and twelve oh nine, each one within the gap of the one before, so they belong to one growing session. Then silence. Five minutes after that last event at twelve oh nine, the session closes at twelve fourteen. A new event at twelve fifteen opens a fresh session, which closes at twelve twenty, and another at twelve twenty-two begins the next. The window size is whatever the user's burst of activity turned out to be. You write this with session window, passing the gap duration. This is how you model a user's visit, a browsing session, a period of active use, where the boundaries aren't on a clock, they're in the behavior.

So three shapes, one timeline. Tumbling tiles the time into equal, separate buckets, one event, one window. Sliding overlaps fixed buckets so an event can sit in several, perfect for rolling metrics. And session lets the data draw its own boundaries, growing and closing around gaps of inactivity.

But here's the question every one of these raises. If a window covers twelve hundred to twelve oh five, how long does Spark keep that window open, waiting? Networks are messy. An event that happened at twelve oh four might not arrive until twelve oh nine, late and out of order. Does it still count? And when is it finally safe to close a window, emit the final answer, and free that memory? Spark can't hold every window open forever. That decision, how long to wait for late data and when to let a window go, has a name. It's called watermarking, and that's the next reel.
